Assume these two translation units are linked together. What does the program print?

```cpp
// unit1.cpp
int value { 7 };

void doubleIt()
{
    value = value * 2;
}
```

```cpp
// unit2.cpp (contains main)
#include <iostream>
extern int value;
void doubleIt();

int main()
{
    doubleIt();
    std::cout << value << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

A developer has two files. After linking, the program crashes with a linker error about multiply defined `counter`. What is the bug?

```cpp
// file_a.cpp
int counter { 0 };
void bumpCounter() { ++counter; }
```

```cpp
// file_b.cpp
#include <iostream>
int counter { 0 };  // intended as forward declaration
void bumpCounter();
int main()
{
    bumpCounter();
    std::cout << counter << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```
